    <procedure>
      <preliminaryRqmts>
        <preliminaryRqmtsDescr>Aircraft on ground, parking brake set, wheels chocked. Ensure brake temperature < 50°C (Ref: AMM 32-41-00-860-801).</preliminaryRqmtsDescr>
        <safety>
          <warning>
            Do not attempt wear pin inspection when brake temperature exceeds 50°C. Hot brakes may result in burns or pin deformation.
          </warning>
          <caution>
            Wear pin gauge tool must be certified and zeroed before each use. Inaccurate readings can lead to unserviceable brakes being retained in operation.
          </caution>
          <note>
            This task is to be performed at every transit check or turnaround where brake usage exceeds 40% wear margin (Ref: MPD Task 32-41-01-210-801).
          </note>
        </safety>
      </preliminaryRqmts>

      <mainProcedure>
        <step>
          <para>Remove brake dust shield access cover (if installed). Refer to IPC 32-41-01, figure 7.</para>
        </step>
        <step>
          <para>Visually inspect wear indicator pin for engagement. If flush or recessed, perform calibrated depth measurement.</para>
        </step>
        <step>
          <para>Insert brake wear gauge tool (PN: GAUGE-WP-777) into access slot. Gently push tool until seated. Do not force.</para>
        </step>
        <step>
          <para>Read calibrated scale. If wear exceeds 0.180 inches (minimum allowable thickness), tag brake for replacement (Ref: CMM 32-41-01).</para>
        </step>
        <step>
          <para>If wear pin shows incorrect projection, remove and replace pin (PN: PIN-WEAR-77A) using 3/8" torque driver set to 35 in-lb.</para>
        </step>
        <step>
          <para>Install new pin. Ensure spring detent engages. Apply torque seal to indicator base threads.</para>
        </step>
      </mainProcedure>

      <closeProcedure>
        <step>
          <para>Reinstall brake access cover and torque screws per AMM 20-50-00.</para>
        </step>
        <step>
          <para>Log measured wear depth and pin replacement date in brake maintenance record.</para>
        </step>
      </closeProcedure>

