        <safety>
          <warning>
            Do not manually operate uplock latch while gear is retracted or under load. Actuator pre-tension may cause sudden latch movement.
          </warning>
          <caution>
            Use only approved lubricants (e.g., MIL-PRF-23827C Type II) to avoid sensor contamination or excess viscosity at cold soak conditions.
          </caution>
          <note>
            Uplock roller and latch lubrication affects both mechanical engagement and proximity sensor reliability. Always retest latch function after application.
          </note>
        </safety>
      </preliminaryRqmts>

      <mainProcedure>
        <step>
          <para>Access uplock latch via maintenance platform at STA 1370 zone. Remove fairing panel 651AB (Ref: AMM 06-00-00 ZONE 700).</para>
        </step>
        <step>
          <para>Visually inspect latch arm, roller, and cam for dirt, grease buildup, or surface damage. Clean using solvent (CPC#458) and a lint-free cloth.</para>
        </step>
        <step>
          <para>Apply lubricant (MIL-PRF-23827C) to cam lobe, latch pin bore, and roller surface using brush or syringe. Avoid lubricant contact with proximity sensors.</para>
        </step>
        <step>
          <para>Manually cycle uplock latch by pushing actuator clevis through full stroke. Observe for smooth engagement and spring return.</para>
        </step>
        <step>
          <para>Perform engagement test by retracting gear (Ref: AMM 32-00-00-710-801). Confirm audible latch “click” and roller lock-in position.</para>
        </step>
        <step>
          <para>Using CMS interface or multimeter, verify proper uplock proximity sensor signal state (Ref: AMM 32-31-02-710-801).</para>
        </step>
      </mainProcedure>

      <closeProcedure>
        <step>
          <para>Reinstall fairing panel. Secure all fasteners and torque to 30 in-lb (Ref: AMM 20-50-00).</para>
        </step>
        <step>
          <para>Document lubrication material, application date, and test result in aircraft gear tracking log (ATA 05-00-00).</para>
        </step>
      </closeProcedure>

